metadata.name: Hyperspace interface #25
metadata.description:
Another one of my belowed GUI in retro-style
Fasten your seat belts, team! We are entering the hyperspace!

IMPORTANT! 
The work has two modes. At 100% page scale it is more stylized as a blurry retro.
You can zoom in to 125% for a crisper, cleaner look. This is done with CTRL + MOUSE SCROLL or with CTRL + "+"
You also need to refresh the page after zooming!

ALSO!
The best view is obtained in the aspect ratio of 1:1 or 4:3, in 16:9 the work requires too many resources and has nothing to show.

metadata.name: Paper screen door | 明かり障子 (akarishouji) #25
metadata.description:
In a traditional Japanese home, you have sliding walls to separate rooms and create privacy. These are made of wood and washi paper and philtre the light from the sun or moon. 

This is exactly the atmosphere I wanted to convey in this minimalist project. The light of the moon or night lighting plays with the layers of paper in their geometric arrangement. 

The white line represents the part of the wood you touch to open or close the wall. 

Press "Enter" to save the iteration. 

In my usual work, I take everyday objects, materials, etc. and play with them. For this series, I inserted texture of polystyrene.

All graphical elements, colours, and random arrangements were created by code using P5.js, texture patterns are embedded in the code. 

6 colours available : red, yellow, green, blue, white, pink.

@Yomu Oyashi August 2022

metadata.name: Gears ⚙ #1
metadata.description:
Gears are fascinating because they are one of the most basic and essential components of so many machines. They are simple yet elegant in their design and function, and they have been used for centuries to power all sorts of machines. 

This piece explores gears in an abstract way, chaining them with different rules - some more realistic than others - creating a variety of different settings.


Controls:
Mousewheel - Zoom in/out
Up/down Arrows - Increase/decrease gear speeds (hold left shift for coarse-tune, left ctrl for fine-tune)
Space - Pause
S - Download image
H - Hide gears
I - Invert gear render order
R - Reverse gear direction
F - Show/hide frame
V - Open plotter export menu
C - Show/hide connectors
T - Enable transparency on grab
D + Click - Hide gear
U - Unhide all gears

Plotter export options:
Default -  The background of your iteration will be exported into the SVG. Only possible for the styles "Brushed Straight", "Cables", and "Gears". 
None - No background
Lines - Parallel lines. Controlled by angle and spacing option
Circles - Concentric circles originating from the middle. Controlled by spacing.
Bg line spacing - spacing of the background lines
Bg line angle - angle of background lines (Only for "Background: Lines")
Min line length - Lines below this length will be discarded


Url parameter options:
lowPerf=1 - disables shadows
noMove=1 - start paused
multGears=X - Not enough gears in your iteration? Substitute X with any number to roughly multiply the amount of gears in your iteration. Use at your own risk ;-)
connectorShade=X - Shadeline spacing on connectors
spokesShade=X - Shadeline spacing on spokes
gearInnerShade - Shadeline spacing on inner gear rings
gearOuterShade - Shadeline spacing on outer gear rings
gearTeethringShade - Shadeline spacing on gear teeth rings


Best viewed on a desktop in Chrome. Requires a decent computer to run smoothly.
Supports touch controls and mobile, however it runs very slowly on firefox mobile.


2% chance to get a golden favicon, which will guarantee a reserve spot for all future mechanical drops.


Created in Vanilla.js

Libraries used: 
noise.js by Joseph Gentle

metadata.name: CrossWorlds #171
metadata.description:
In 2057 an error occurred in the particle accelerator machine causing a diversion in space-time that leads to duplication of our world. Scientists discovered that they can travel to these "CrossWorlds" with wormholes plagued by singularities occurring at weakened points of the fabric between worlds. In time, some worlds became hostile to each other, tried to plunder their natural resources, and take over civilizations but other worlds learned how to co-exist peacefully...
------------------
Animation_
Press R: Rotates the world 180°
Idle: Default animation cycles from corner to corner
Mouse: Cursor-dependent animation
MobileDevice: Controls the animation with the orientation of the device. (Android only)
------------------
Live-view_
Resolution: Add "&res=" end of your url with a resolution multiplier. (0.5-6)
Press S: Saves the current scene (Default 1600x1600 px).
Press L: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as PNG.
Press D: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as SVG.
------------------
Created with p5js.

metadata.name: a pale reflection #108
metadata.description:
a canvas is prepared; grids and vignette applied.

marks are added (or not)

a drawing method is chosen

the drawing method is iterated, resulting in a heavily stippled image

the image is sent to a shader

various maths occur inside the shader

the resulting shaded image is then given a border

and thus to the screen

a pale reflection - original music here: https://rtsixty.bandcamp.com/track/pale-reflection 
listen while waiting to be signed.

99.9% of royalties to original minter.

metadata.name: Broken Symmetries #3/3 #61
metadata.description:
"I think a lot of us feel, when we look at the Dow Jones plunging, alienated - you do feel as if we're in the grip of some alien force that slipped human control."
Robert Harris

This piece is the third in a planed series of three intended as studies on composition.

It is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ original resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution
- s : download canvas as SVG @ current resolution; This can be used with a plotter.

This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

metadata.name: Un1 #134
metadata.description:
Un1 is inspired by Unicode block element characters, and my love of minimal and monochromatic art. 

With Un1 I was looking for the final result to have a slightly degraded or low-res look. To that end the pixel density is intentionally set low, (saved images [s] will be based on your browser window size) so that when the piece is enlarged or printed the output has a degraded look.

This artwork was coded using the p5.js library

metadata.name: Wanderlust #33
metadata.description:
The intent of this piece is to feed the need of discovery, of venturing into the unknown, tumbling into hidden beauty.

The early morning fog washes away colour and resolution, leaving only silhouettes to guide you. 



Made in Cables.gl

----

Important infos:

-2 Pre-modelled 3d rocks
-Handpainted grass and flowers PNGs as masks
-First couple of frames might flash some weird stuff while all IFs are calculated
-This piece runs on your gpu, and might explode old dusty pcs as i'm not the best in optmization
